"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:984
#, no-wrap
msgid "`umask` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:987
msgid "The `umask` command allows you to display and modify the mask."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:988
#, no-wrap
msgid "umask [option] [mode]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:993
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ umask 033\n"
"$ umask\n"
"0033\n"
"$ umask -S\n"
"u=rwx,g=r,o=r\n"
"$ touch umask_033\n"
"$ ls -la  umask_033\n"
"-rw-r--r-- 1 rockstar rockstar 0 nov.   4 16:44 umask_033\n"
"$ umask 025\n"
"$ umask -S\n"
"u=rwx,g=rx,o=w\n"
"$ touch umask_025\n"
"$ ls -la  umask_025\n"
"-rw-r---w- 1 rockstar rockstar 0 nov.   4 16:44 umask_025\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1013
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option |\tDescription                     |\n"
"|--------|----------------------------------|\n"
"| `-S`   | Symbolic display of file rights. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1017
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `umask` does not affect existing files. `umask -S` displays the file rights (without the execute right) of the files that will be created. So, it is not the display of the mask used to subtract the maximum value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1021
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `umask` modifies the mask until the disconnection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1025
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `umask` command belongs to bash's built-in commands, so when you use `man umask`, all built-in commands will be displayed. If you only want to view the help of `umask`, you need to use the `help umask` command.\n"
msgstr ""

